{
  "text": "PUFAs may have a role in autotaxin (ATX)/lysophosphatidic acid axis (LPA). ATX is a lysophospholipase D, which converts lysophosphatidylcholine (LPC) to LPA [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . ATX synthesis can be up-regulated in inflammatory tissues, leading to the production of LPA, which have an important role in cell growth and motility; ATX/LPA axis could represent a key pathway in immune cells and inflammatory disorders [CITATION_3] . Notably, in rheumatoid arthritis synovial fibroblasts TNF-α can induce ATX expression [CITATION_4] and increasing evidence has shown that LPA1 receptor could represent an intriguing therapeutic option [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Of interest, in a cancer model carboxyl group-containing PUFAs inhibited LPAinduced calcium/RhoA signalling pathway [CITATION_7] .",
  "correct_citation": {
